        {
          "type": "pronunciation",
          "title": "Pronunciation Guide",
          "tips": [
            {
              "focus": "ř",
              "description": "The 'ř' sound is unique to Czech. It's like rolling an 'r' while simultaneously making a 'zh' sound (like the 's' in 'measure'). Try vibrating your tongue against the roof of your mouth while saying 'rzh'.",
              "czechExamples": ["Dobrý", "před", "přítel"],
              "audioSrc": "/cz/audio/01-greetings/lesson-01/pron-r"
            },
            {
              "focus": "ě",
              "description": "The letter 'ě' (e with háček) sounds like 'ye' as in 'yes'. It also palatalizes (softens) the preceding consonant. In 'Děkuji', the 'dě' sounds like 'dyeh'.",
              "czechExamples": ["Děkuji", "mě", "oběd"],
              "audioSrc": "/cz/audio/01-greetings/lesson-01/pron-e"
            },
            {
              "focus": "j",
              "description": "Czech 'j' is always pronounced like 'y' in 'yes', never like English 'j'. So 'jak' sounds like 'yahk'.",
              "czechExamples": ["Jak", "jmenuji", "jazyk"],
              "audioSrc": "/cz/audio/01-greetings/lesson-01/pron-j"
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "vocabulary": [
        { "czech": "Dobrý den", "english": "Good day", "partOfSpeech": "phrase" },
        { "czech": "Jak", "english": "How", "partOfSpeech": "adverb" },
        { "czech": "se", "english": "oneself (reflexive pronoun)", "partOfSpeech": "pronoun" },
        { "czech": "máte", "english": "you have/are (formal, 2nd person plural)", "partOfSpeech": "verb" },
        { "czech": "Děkuji", "english": "Thank you", "partOfSpeech": "verb" },
        { "czech": "dobře", "english": "well/good", "partOfSpeech": "adverb" },
        { "czech": "jmenuji se", "english": "I call myself / my name is", "partOfSpeech": "verb phrase" },
        { "czech": "Těší mě", "english": "Pleased to meet you", "partOfSpeech": "phrase" },
        { "czech": "odkud", "english": "from where", "partOfSpeech": "adverb" },
        { "czech": "jsem", "english": "I am", "partOfSpeech": "verb" }
      ],
      "grammarNotes": "## Formality in Czech\n\nCzech has two levels of formality:\n- **Ty** (informal) — used with friends, family, children\n- **Vy** (formal) — used with strangers, in business, with elders\n\nAlways start with formal **Vy** unless invited otherwise. **Dobrý den** works in all situations (literally 'Good day')."
    },
    {
      "id": "01-greetings-02",
      "moduleId": "01-greetings",
      "title": "Rozloučení a zdvořilosti",
      "titleEn": "Goodbyes & Politeness",
